No, apparently not. The creature just hissed and tried to fly directly at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite his size, Thassalin was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi let out a cry when she almost lost her grip on Thassalin's smooth scales.
"How can we kill her?," screamed Nyssi.
"Target their heads!"
"That will be difficult!"
Thassalin hissed and then drew a circle, closer to the mountain he called home. The dark beast followed, but became slightly panicky when it was hit by a beam of fire from behind. It had not realized that it was no longer alone. It became even more panicked when Thassalin slowed down and then flung his tail against her head, throwing her off course.
Growling and hissing, she flew upward and spat into the air. Everything suddenly turned dark, as if the monster sucked the light from the sky into itself and replaced it with a cloud of eternal night.
As he suddenly could see nothing anymore, Thassalin tried to retreat. He felt himself scraping along the tree crowns before finally plunging into a clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen and shot directly at him, dragging the black cloud with her.
"Kayel!", shouted Tenuk as he glided out of the cloud and began circling to look for Nyssi and Thassalin in the darkness below. "What should we do now, Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Down below, Nyssi painfully got to her feet. She was sure she had broken something, but her peculiar, supernatural healing powers had already begun to take effect. Unfortunately, this was not the case for Thassalin. He leaned exhausted against the only tree that had not collapsed under his weight. Nyssi tried her best to get close to Thassalin, but she could barely see two meters. Everything was pitch black and shrouded in eerie shadows. And in that shadow, something was screaming and screeching.
A fearsome, armored tail crashed beside Nyssi onto the ground and knocked her down. However, she noticed that the tail was just flailing wildly and not intentionally trying to hit her. The beast, or rather the little that Nyssi could see and hear of it, growled and swiped at the shadows it had created with its claws. Something shot through the darkness, stabbed the monster, and confused it.
Suddenly, a gunshot cracked through the mist, and the monster fell silent, collapsed onto the ground, and lay motionless. The darkness around them dissipated, and they saw what had happened: Kayel stood on the beast, heavily panting while holding his rifle.
"That was... The craziest shadow leap I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", Kabel gasped for breath. His eyes glowed almost black, and a dark energy swirled around his body. But as he was still speaking, color returned to his armor, and his eyes took on their normal yellow hue again.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. They had all known that Kayel possessed these strange shadow abilities. He rarely used them because most people found them eerie and quite frightening. But Nyssi hadn't known that Kayel could also use these powers in any kind of darkness. And the way Kayel was behaving, he apparently was quite surprised as well.
"Are you okay?" broke out of Nyssi.
"Yes, I'm fine. I killed something, I'll be back to normal in a moment." Kayel examined his work as Tenuk swooped down, landed beside him, and resumed his normal spastic form.
Now that the beast was no longer moving, they could see better what it was. Its skin was raven-black and slimy, but the slime remained firmly attached to its body. It had four wings and four extremities, all ending in long, thin claws, and two straight horns extended from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what the hell they were facing, something screeched and jumped out of a nearby bush. However, it didn't reach them because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, causing the monster to skid to a stop in front of Nyssi's feet. Nyssi didn't want to take any chances. She grabbed her shotgun, fired without thinking at its head, and the creature died on the spot.
"Ups…," muttered Retvik from the driver's seat before awkwardly turning off the engine and getting out of the truck. "Uh, that wasn't actually intentional. Are you all okay?"
"You missed the whole action," scolded Tenuk. "Where were you?"
"You all just left me behind. I came as fast as I could...", sighed Retvik. "May I ask what those terrible beasts are?"
Fortunately, Retvik's question was answered by Thassalin, who had managed to get back on his feet. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit dazed, but not seriously injured.
"YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTIIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES THAT WERE LEAVING HERE WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"you mean that terrible god-monster creature that we... helped kill?" stuttered Tenuk.
"YES. EXACTLY THAT. MAYBE THERE ARE MORE. BUT I COULDN'T SHOOT IN THE HEAD. I DON'T HAVE A GUN. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, OR?" Thassalin limped to Kayel and patted his head. "THANK YOU VERY MUCH, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST NOT SO MURDEROUS AND NOT SO ABLE AT KILLING WHOLE UNIVERSES."
"Uh... thanks... I guess...," Kayel shrugged. "So, are we done here?"
Nyssi shrugged. She grabbed her camera and took a few photos of the now definitely dead creatures. Then she pulled out her favorite weapon, the ornate god-of-death dagger, and began sawing off one of the beast's horns. She then moved on to the second one. But just as Nyssi was finishing, the creatures suddenly burst into flames and turned into a pile of ash in an instant. The same thing happened to the horns Nyssi had cut off.
"Okay, that's both practical and impractical at the same time...", sighed Nyssi. "But at least I have the photos, hopefully."
